  "slug": "tiffin",
  "title": "Tiffin",
  "subtitle": "Fridge-set chocolate biscuit traybake",
  "excerpt": "A no-bake traybake of butter, golden syrup, cocoa, broken digestives, dried fruit, and dark chocolate. Fridge-set, sliced cold. Simple and very reliable.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Tiffin and chocolate biscuit cake are the same bake by different names. The recipe is documented in British cookery columns throughout the mid-twentieth century. The technique (melting butter, syrup, and cocoa then binding broken biscuits) appears in domestic encyclopaedias from the 1940s onwards.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Tiffin requires no oven and almost no technique. The skill, such as it is, is in the ratio: enough fat and syrup to bind the broken biscuits firmly, not so much that it becomes greasy. The dried fruit adds chew; the salt anchors the sweetness. The topping is a straight melt of dark chocolate, no ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "tempering chocolate",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpa9tpvr0000owv4l5ah5qfb"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " needed unless you want the professional snap and gloss.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
